# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qr-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In numerical linear algebra, the **QR algorithm** or **QR iteration** is an eigenvalue algorithm: that is, a procedure to calculate the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The QR algorithm was developed in the late 1950s by John G.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The basic idea is to perform a QR decomposition, writing the matrix as a product of an orthogonal matrix and an upper triangular matrix, multiply the factors in the reverse order, and iterate.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Formally, let *A* be a real matrix of which we want to compute the eigenvalues, and let *A*0 := *A*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] At the k-th step (starting with *k* = 0), we compute the QR decomposition *A**k* = *Q**k* *R**k* where *Q**k* is an orthogonal matrix (i.e., *Q*T = *Q*−1) and *R**k* is an upper triangular matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The algorithm is numerically stable because it proceeds by *orthogonal* similarity transforms.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Under certain conditions, the matrices *A**k* converge to a triangular matrix, the Schur form of *A*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The eigenvalues of a triangular matrix are listed on the diagonal, and the eigenvalue problem is solved.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In testing for convergence it is impractical to require exact zeros, but the Gershgorin circle theorem provides a bound on the error.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] If the matrices converge, then the eigenvalues along the diagonal will appear according to their geometric multiplicity.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] To guarantee convergence, A must be a symmetric matrix, and for all non zero eigenvalues $\lambda$ there must not be a corresponding eigenvalue $-\lambda$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Due to the fact that a single QR iteration has a cost of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ and the convergence is linear, the standard QR algorithm is extremely expensive to compute, especially considering it is not guaranteed to converge.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In the above crude form the iterations are relatively expensive.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] (For QR decomposition, the Householder reflectors are multiplied only on the left, but for the Hessenberg case they are multiplied on both left and right.) Determining the QR decomposition of an upper Hessenberg matrix costs ${\textstyle 6n^{2}+{\mathcal {O}}(n)}$ arithmetic operations.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Moreover, because the Hessenberg form is already nearly upper-triangular (it has just one nonzero entry below each diagonal), using it as a starting point reduces the number of steps required for convergence of the QR algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] If the original matrix is symmetric, then the upper Hessenberg matrix is also symmetric and thus tridiagonal, and so are all the *A**k*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In this case reaching Hessenberg form costs ${\textstyle {\tfrac {4}{3}}n^{3}+{\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})}$ arithmetic operations using a technique based on Householder reduction.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Determining the QR decomposition of a symmetric tridiagonal matrix costs ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ operations.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The purpose of the QR iteration step is to shrink one of these $a_{k,k-1}$ elements so that effectively a small block along the diagonal is split off from the bulk of the matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In the case of a real eigenvalue that is usually the $1\times 1$ block in the lower right corner (in which case element $a_{nn}$ holds that eigenvalue), whereas in the case of a pair of conjugate complex eigenvalues it is the $2\times 2$ block in the lower right corner.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The rate of convergence depends on the separation between eigenvalues, so a practical algorithm will use shifts, either explicit or implicit, to increase separation and accelerate convergence.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] A typical symmetric QR algorithm isolates each eigenvalue (then reduces the size of the matrix) with only one or two iterations, making it efficient as well as robust.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This produces the upper triangular matrix $R=G_{n-1}\dotsb G_{1}(A-\mu I)$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The orthogonal factor Q would be $G_{1}^{\mathrm {T} }G_{2}^{\mathrm {T} }\dotsb G_{n-1}^{\mathrm {T} }$ , but it is neither necessary nor efficient to produce that explicitly.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This produces the matrix $RQ=RG_{1}^{\mathrm {T} }G_{2}^{\mathrm {T} }\dotsb G_{n-1}^{\mathrm {T} }$ , which is again on Hessenberg form.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Finally undo the shift by adding $\mu$ to all diagonal entries.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Since Q commutes with I , we have that $A'=Q^{\mathrm {T} }(A-\mu I)Q+\mu I=Q^{\mathrm {T} }AQ$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The purpose of the shift is to change which Givens rotations are chosen.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] It is not necessary to exhibit $\theta$ ; the factors c and s can be determined directly from elements in the matrix $G_{i}$ should act on.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Nor is it necessary to produce the whole matrix; multiplication (from the left) by $G_{i}$ only affects rows i and $i+1$ , so it is easier to just update those two rows in place.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Likewise, for the Step 3 multiplication by $G_{i}^{\mathrm {T} }$ from the right, it is sufficient to remember i , c , and s .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] If $|h_{n-1,n-1}|\gg |h_{n,n-1}|$ , as is typically the case when we approach convergence, then $c\approx 1$ and $|s|\ll 1$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] But now we reach Step 3, and need to start rotating data between columns.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Practically that means $O(1)$ iterations per eigenvalue suffice for convergence, and thus overall we can complete in $O(n)$ QR steps, each of which does a mere $O(n^{2})$ arithmetic operations (or as little as $O(n)$ operations, in the case that A is symmetric).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The basic QR algorithm can be visualized in the case where *A* is a positive-definite symmetric matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In that case, *A* can be depicted as an ellipse in 2 dimensions or an ellipsoid in higher dimensions.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The relationship between the input to the algorithm and a single iteration can then be depicted as in Figure 1 (click to see an animation).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Note that the LR algorithm is depicted alongside the QR algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] A single iteration causes the ellipse to tilt or "fall" towards the x-axis.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In the event where the large semi-axis of the ellipse is parallel to the x-axis, one iteration of QR does nothing.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Another situation where the algorithm "does nothing" is when the large semi-axis is parallel to the y-axis instead of the x-axis.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In that event, the ellipse can be thought of as balancing precariously without being able to fall in either direction.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In both situations, the matrix is diagonal.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] A situation where an iteration of the algorithm "does nothing" is called a fixed point.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The strategy employed by the algorithm is iteration towards a fixed-point.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Observe that one fixed point is stable while the other is unstable.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] If the ellipse were tilted away from the unstable fixed point by a very small amount, one iteration of QR would cause the ellipse to tilt away from the fixed point instead of towards.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Eventually though, the algorithm would converge to a different fixed point, but it would take a long time.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] It's worth pointing out that finding even a single eigenvector of a symmetric matrix is not computable (in exact real arithmetic according to the definitions in computable analysis).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This difficulty exists whenever the multiplicities of a matrix's eigenvalues are not knowable.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] On the other hand, the same problem does not exist for finding eigenvalues.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The eigenvalues of a matrix are always computable.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] We will now discuss how these difficulties manifest in the basic QR algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Recall that the ellipses represent positive-definite symmetric matrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] As the two eigenvalues of the input matrix approach each other, the input ellipse changes into a circle.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] A circle corresponds to a multiple of the identity matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] A near-circle corresponds to a near-multiple of the identity matrix whose eigenvalues are nearly equal to the diagonal entries of the matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Therefore, the problem of approximately finding the eigenvalues is shown to be easy in that case.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] But notice what happens to the semi-axes of the ellipses.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] An iteration of QR (or LR) tilts the semi-axes less and less as the input ellipse gets closer to being a circle.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The eigenvectors can only be known when the semi-axes are parallel to the x-axis and y-axis.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The number of iterations needed to achieve near-parallelism increases without bound as the input ellipse becomes more circular.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] While it may be impossible to compute the eigendecomposition of an arbitrary symmetric matrix, it is always possible to perturb the matrix by an arbitrarily small amount and compute the eigendecomposition of the resulting matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In the case when the matrix is depicted as a near-circle, the matrix can be replaced with one whose depiction is a perfect circle.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In that case, the matrix is a multiple of the identity matrix, and its eigendecomposition is immediate.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Be aware though that the resulting eigenbasis can be quite far from the original eigenbasis.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The slowdown when the ellipse gets more circular has a converse: It turns out that when the ellipse gets more stretched - and less circular - then the rotation of the ellipse becomes faster.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Such a stretch can be induced when the matrix M which the ellipse represents gets replaced with $M-\lambda I$ where $\lambda$ is approximately the smallest eigenvalue of M .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In this case, the ratio of the two semi-axes of the ellipse approaches $\infty$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In higher dimensions, shifting like this makes the length of the smallest semi-axis of an ellipsoid small relative to the other semi-axes, which speeds up convergence to the smallest eigenvalue, but does not speed up convergence to the other eigenvalues.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This becomes useless when the smallest eigenvalue is fully determined, so the matrix must then be *deflated*, which simply means removing its last row and column.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The issue with the unstable fixed point also needs to be addressed.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The shifting heuristic is often designed to deal with this problem as well: Practical shifts are often discontinuous and randomised.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Wilkinson's shift—which is well-suited for symmetric matrices like the ones we're visualising—is in particular discontinuous.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] In modern computational practice, the QR algorithm is performed in an implicit version which makes the use of multiple shifts easier to introduce.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Then successive Householder transformations of size $r+1$ are performed in order to return the working matrix $A_{k}$ to upper Hessenberg form.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This operation is known as *bulge chasing*, due to the peculiar shape of the non-zero entries of the matrix along the steps of the algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] As in the first version, deflation is performed as soon as one of the sub-diagonal entries of $A_{k}$ is sufficiently small.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Since in the modern implicit version of the procedure no QR decompositions are explicitly performed, some authors, for instance Watkins, suggested changing its name to *Francis algorithm*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Golub and Van Loan use the term *Francis QR step*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The QR algorithm can be seen as a more sophisticated variation of the basic "power" eigenvalue algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Recall that the power algorithm repeatedly multiplies *A* times a single vector, normalizing after each iteration.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The vector converges to an eigenvector of the largest eigenvalue.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Instead, the QR algorithm works with a complete basis of vectors, using QR decomposition to renormalize (and orthogonalize).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] For a symmetric matrix *A*, upon convergence, *AQ* = *QΛ*, where *Λ* is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues to which *A* converged, and where *Q* is a composite of all the orthogonal similarity transforms required to get there.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Thus the columns of *Q* are the eigenvectors.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The QR algorithm was preceded by the *LR algorithm*, which uses the LU decomposition instead of the QR decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The QR algorithm is more stable, so the LR algorithm is rarely used nowadays.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] However, it represents an important step in the development of the QR algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The LR algorithm was developed in the early 1950s by Heinz Rutishauser, who worked at that time as a research assistant of Eduard Stiefel at ETH Zurich.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Stiefel suggested that Rutishauser use the sequence of moments *y*0T *A**k* *x*0, *k* = 0, 1, ...
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] (where *x*0 and *y*0 are arbitrary vectors) to find the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Rutishauser took an algorithm of Alexander Aitken for this task and developed it into the *quotient–difference algorithm* or *qd algorithm*.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] After arranging the computation in a suitable shape, he discovered that the qd algorithm is in fact the iteration *A**k* = *L**k**U**k* (LU decomposition), *A**k*+1 = *U**k**L**k*, applied on a tridiagonal matrix, from which the LR algorithm follows.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] One variant of the *QR algorithm*, *the Golub-Kahan-Reinsch* algorithm starts with reducing a general matrix into a bidiagonal one.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] This variant of the *QR algorithm* for the computation of singular values was first described by Golub & Kahan (1965).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The LAPACK subroutine DBDSQR implements this iterative method, with some modifications to cover the case where the singular values are very small (Demmel & Kahan 1990).
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] Together with a first step using Householder reflections and, if appropriate, QR decomposition, this forms the DGESVD routine for the computation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/francis-algorithm] The QR algorithm can also be implemented in infinite dimensions with corresponding convergence results.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] In numerical linear algebra, a **Givens rotation** is a rotation in the plane spanned by two coordinates axes.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Givens rotations are named after Wallace Givens, who introduced them to numerical analysts in the 1950s while he was working at Argonne National Laboratory.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] A Givens rotation acting on a matrix from the left is a row operation, moving data between rows but always within the same column.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Unlike the elementary operation of row-addition, a Givens rotation changes both of the rows addressed by it.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] As with row-addition, algorithms often choose this angle so that one specific element becomes zero, and whatever happens in remaining columns is considered acceptable side-effects.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] A Givens rotation acting on a matrix from the right is instead a column operation, moving data between two columns but always within the same row.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] In this case the effect on the four elements affected by both rotations is more complicated; a Jacobi rotation is such a conjugate action to the end of zeroing the two off-diagonal elements among these four.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The main use of Givens rotations in numerical linear algebra is to transform vectors or matrices into a special form with zeros in certain coefficients.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This effect can, for example, be employed for computing the QR decomposition of a matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] One advantage over Householder transformations is that they can easily be parallelised, and another is that often for very sparse matrices they have a lower operation count.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] where *c* = cos *θ* and *s* = sin *θ* appear at the intersections ith and jth rows and columns.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The product *G*(*i*, *j*, *θ*)**x** represents a counterclockwise rotation of the vector **x** in the (*i*, *j*) plane of θ radians, hence the name Givens rotation.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] When a Givens rotation matrix, *G*(*i*, *j*, *θ*), multiplies another matrix, A, from the left, *G A*, only rows i and j of A are affected.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Thus we restrict attention to the following counterclockwise problem.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Explicit calculation of θ is rarely necessary or desirable.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] However, the computation for r may overflow or underflow.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] An alternative formulation avoiding this problem (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §5.1.8) is implemented as the hypot function in many programming languages.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The following Fortran code is a minimalistic implementation of Givens rotation for real numbers.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] If the input values 'a' or 'b' are frequently zero, the code may be optimized to handle these cases as presented here.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Furthermore, as Edward Anderson discovered in improving LAPACK, a previously overlooked numerical consideration is continuity.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] To achieve this, we require r to be positive.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The following MATLAB/GNU Octave code illustrates the algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The IEEE 754 `copysign(x,y)` function, provides a safe and cheap way to copy the sign of `y` to `x`.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] If that is not available, |*x*|⋅sgn(*y*), using the abs and sgn functions, is an alternative as done above.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] two iterations of the Givens rotation (note that the Givens rotation algorithm used here differs slightly from above) yield an upper triangular matrix in order to compute the QR decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Zeroing element (3,2) finishes off the process.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This new matrix A3 is the upper triangular matrix needed to perform an iteration of the QR decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This completes two iterations of the Givens Rotation and calculating the QR decomposition can now be done.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Likewise, storing the full Q matrix amounts to $n^{2}$ elements, but each Givens matrix is fully specified the pairs $(c,s)$ and $(i,j),$ and $n-1$ of them can thus be stored in $4n-4$ elements.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] A Givens rotation in the complex case would have to be a unitary matrix which maps a nonzero vector ${\begin{pmatrix}w\\z\end{pmatrix}}\in \mathbb {C} ^{2}$ to some ${\begin{pmatrix}r\\0\end{pmatrix}}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] (Golub & Van Loan 2013, §5.1.13) suggest the specialised form ${\begin{pmatrix}\cos(\theta )&-\sin(\theta )e^{i\phi }\\\sin(\theta )e^{-i\phi }&\cos(\theta )\end{pmatrix}}$ (coinciding with the above when w is real) for a Givens rotation.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This more complicated initialisation can be justified by the observation that since half the matrix elements are real, fewer arithmetic operations are needed when applying this rotation.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Note however that having only two real degrees of freedom means the r component of the result cannot in general be made real.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] A more elementary approach to the same end is to first multiply both rows being targeted by unit magnitude complex numbers of appropriate phase, so that both elements in the column considered become real – then a real Givens rotation suffices for zeroing out one of those entires.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Here we save some arithmetic operations because multiplication by D acts on each row separately, and multiplication by G has real coefficients throughout.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] In Clifford algebras and its child structures such as geometric algebras, rotations are represented by bivectors.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Givens rotations are represented by the exterior product of the basis vectors.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] Given that they are endomorphisms they can be composed with each other as many times as desired, keeping in mind that *g* ∘ *f* ≠ *f* ∘ *g*.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] These three Givens rotations composed can generate any rotation matrix according to Davenport's chained rotation theorem.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This means that they can transform the standard basis of the space to any other frame in the space.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] When rotations are performed in the right order, the values of the rotation angles of the final frame will be equal to the Euler angles of the final frame in the corresponding convention.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] For the same reason, any rotation matrix in 3D can be decomposed in a product of three of these rotation operators.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The meaning of the composition of two Givens rotations *g* ∘ *f* is an operator that transforms vectors first by f and then by g, being f and g rotations about one axis of basis of the space.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] This is similar to the extrinsic rotation equivalence for Euler angles.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The following table shows the three Givens rotations equivalent to the different Euler angles conventions using extrinsic composition (composition of rotations about the basis axes) of active rotations and the right-handed rule for the positive sign of the angles.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] The notation has been simplified in such a way that *c*1 means cos *θ*1 and *s*2 means sin *θ*2).
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] As rotations are applied just in the opposite order of the Euler angles table of rotations, this table is the same but swapping indexes 1 and 3 in the angles associated with the corresponding entry.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] An entry like *zxy* means to apply first the *y* rotation, then *x*, and finally *z*, in the basis axes.
[src:qr-algorithm/givens-rotation] All the compositions assume the right hand convention for the matrices that are multiplied, yielding the following results.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] In mathematics, particularly linear algebra and numerical analysis, the **Gram–Schmidt process** or Gram-Schmidt algorithm is a way of finding a set of two or more vectors that are perpendicular to each other.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] By technical definition, it is a method of constructing an orthonormal basis from a set of vectors in an inner product space, most commonly the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ equipped with the standard inner product.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The Gram–Schmidt process takes a finite, linearly independent set of vectors $S=\{\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}\}$ for *k* ≤ *n* and generates an orthogonal set $S'=\{\mathbf {u} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {u} _{k}\}$ that spans the same k -dimensional subspace of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as S .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The method is named after Jørgen Pedersen Gram and Erhard Schmidt, but Pierre-Simon Laplace had been familiar with it before Gram and Schmidt.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] In the theory of Lie group decompositions, it is generalized by the Iwasawa decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The application of the Gram–Schmidt process to the column vectors of a full column rank matrix yields the QR decomposition (it is decomposed into an orthogonal and a triangular matrix).
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] This means that $\operatorname {proj} _{\mathbf {u} }(\mathbf {v} )$ is the orthogonal projection of $\mathbf {v}$ onto the line spanned by $\mathbf {u}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] If $\mathbf {u}$ is the zero vector, then $\operatorname {proj} _{\mathbf {u} }(\mathbf {v} )$ is defined as the zero vector.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The sequence $\mathbf {u} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {u} _{k}$ is the required system of orthogonal vectors, and the normalized vectors $\mathbf {e} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {e} _{k}$ form an orthonormal set.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The calculation of the sequence $\mathbf {u} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {u} _{k}$ is known as *Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization*, and the calculation of the sequence $\mathbf {e} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {e} _{k}$ is known as *Gram–Schmidt orthonormalization*.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] To check that these formulas yield an orthogonal sequence, first compute $\langle \mathbf {u} _{1},\mathbf {u} _{2}\rangle$ by substituting the above formula for $\mathbf {u} _{2}$ : we get zero.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Then use this to compute $\langle \mathbf {u} _{1},\mathbf {u} _{3}\rangle$ again by substituting the formula for $\mathbf {u} _{3}$ : we get zero.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] For arbitrary k the proof is accomplished by mathematical induction.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Geometrically, this method proceeds as follows: to compute $\mathbf {u} _{i}$ , it projects $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ orthogonally onto the subspace U generated by $\mathbf {u} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {u} _{i-1}$ , which is the same as the subspace generated by $\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{i-1}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The vector $\mathbf {u} _{i}$ is then defined to be the difference between $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ and this projection, guaranteed to be orthogonal to all of the vectors in the subspace U .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The Gram–Schmidt process also applies to a linearly independent countably infinite sequence {**v***i*}*i*.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The result is an orthogonal (or orthonormal) sequence {**u***i*}*i* such that for natural number n: the algebraic span of $\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{n}$ is the same as that of $\mathbf {u} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {u} _{n}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] If the Gram–Schmidt process is applied to a linearly dependent sequence, it outputs the **0** vector on the i th step, assuming that $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ is a linear combination of $\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{i-1}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] If an orthonormal basis is to be produced, then the algorithm should test for zero vectors in the output and discard them because no multiple of a zero vector can have a length of 1.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The number of vectors output by the algorithm will then be the dimension of the space spanned by the original inputs.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] In particular, when applied to a (algebraic) basis of a Hilbert space (or, more generally, a basis of any dense subspace), it yields a (functional-analytic) orthonormal basis.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Denote by $\operatorname {GS} (\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k})$ the result of applying the Gram–Schmidt process to a collection of vectors $\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Let $g\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be orthogonal (with respect to the given inner product).
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Further, a parametrized version of the Gram–Schmidt process yields a (strong) deformation retraction of the general linear group $\mathrm {GL} (\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ onto the orthogonal group $O(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] When this process is implemented on a computer, the vectors $\mathbf {u} _{k}$ are often not quite orthogonal, due to rounding errors.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] For the Gram–Schmidt process as described above (sometimes referred to as "classical Gram–Schmidt") this loss of orthogonality is particularly bad; therefore, it is said that the (classical) Gram–Schmidt process is numerically unstable.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The Gram–Schmidt process can be stabilized by a small modification; this version is sometimes referred to as **modified Gram-Schmidt** or MGS.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] This approach gives the same result as the original formula in exact arithmetic and introduces smaller errors in finite-precision arithmetic.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] This method is used in the previous animation, when the intermediate $\mathbf {v} '_{3}$ vector is used when orthogonalizing the blue vector $\mathbf {v} _{3}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Here is another description of the modified algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Next, we orthogonalize those remaining vectors against $\mathbf {u} _{2}=\mathbf {v} _{2}^{(1)}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Proceeding in this manner we find the full set of orthogonal vectors $\mathbf {u} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {u} _{n}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] If orthonormal vectors are desired, then we normalize as we go, so that the denominators in the subtraction formulas turn into ones.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The following MATLAB algorithm implements classical Gram–Schmidt orthonormalization.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The vectors **v**1, ..., **v***k* (columns of matrix `V`, so that `V(:,j)` is the j th vector) are replaced by orthonormal vectors (columns of `U`) which span the same subspace.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The cost of this algorithm is asymptotically O(*nk*2) floating point operations, where n is the dimensionality of the vectors.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] If the rows {**v**1, ..., **v***k*} are written as a matrix A , then applying Gaussian elimination to the augmented matrix $\left[AA^{\mathsf {T}}|A\right]$ will produce the orthogonalized vectors in place of A .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] However the matrix $AA^{\mathsf {T}}$ must be brought to row echelon form, using only the row operation of adding a scalar multiple of one row to another.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The result of the Gram–Schmidt process may be expressed in a non-recursive formula using determinants.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Note that the expression for $\mathbf {u} _{k}$ is a "formal" determinant, i.e. the matrix contains both scalars and vectors; the meaning of this expression is defined to be the result of a cofactor expansion along the row of vectors.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The determinant formula for the Gram-Schmidt is computationally (exponentially) slower than the recursive algorithms described above; it is mainly of theoretical interest.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The results can equivalently be expressed as $\mathbf {u} _{k}=\mathbf {v} _{k}\wedge \mathbf {v} _{k-1}\wedge \cdot \cdot \cdot \wedge \mathbf {v} _{1}(\mathbf {v} _{k-1}\wedge \cdot \cdot \cdot \wedge \mathbf {v} _{1})^{-1},$ which is closely related to the expression using determinants above.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Other orthogonalization algorithms use Householder transformations or Givens rotations.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The algorithms using Householder transformations are more stable than the stabilized Gram–Schmidt process.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] On the other hand, the Gram–Schmidt process produces the j th orthogonalized vector after the j th iteration, while orthogonalization using Householder reflections produces all the vectors only at the end.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] This makes only the Gram–Schmidt process applicable for iterative methods like the Arnoldi iteration.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Yet another alternative is motivated by the use of Cholesky decomposition for inverting the matrix of the normal equations in linear least squares.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Let V be a full column rank matrix, whose columns need to be orthogonalized.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The matrix $V^{*}V$ is Hermitian and positive definite, so it can be written as $V^{*}V=LL^{*},$ using the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The lower triangular matrix L with strictly positive diagonal entries is invertible.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Then columns of the matrix $U=V\left(L^{-1}\right)^{*}$ are orthonormal and span the same subspace as the columns of the original matrix V .
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The explicit use of the product $V^{*}V$ makes the algorithm unstable, especially if the product's condition number is large.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Nevertheless, this algorithm is used in practice and implemented in some software packages because of its high efficiency and simplicity.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] In quantum mechanics there are several orthogonalization schemes with characteristics better suited for certain applications than original Gram–Schmidt.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Nevertheless, it remains a popular and effective algorithm for even the largest electronic structure calculations.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization can be done in strongly-polynomial time.
[src:qr-algorithm/gram-schmidt-process] The run-time analysis is similar to that of Gaussian elimination.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] In linear algebra, a **Hessenberg matrix** is a special kind of square matrix, one that is "almost" triangular.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] To be exact, an **upper Hessenberg matrix** has zero entries below the first subdiagonal, and a **lower Hessenberg matrix** has zero entries above the first superdiagonal.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A **Hessenberg decomposition** is a matrix decomposition of a matrix A into a unitary matrix P and a Hessenberg matrix H such that $PHP^{*}=A$ where $P^{*}$ denotes the conjugate transpose.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A square $n\times n$ matrix A is said to be in **upper Hessenberg form** or to be an **upper Hessenberg matrix** if $a_{i,j}=0$ for all $i,j$ with $i>j+1$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] An upper Hessenberg matrix is called **unreduced** if all subdiagonal entries are nonzero, i.e. if $a_{i+1,i}\neq 0$ for all $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n-1\}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A square $n\times n$ matrix A is said to be in **lower Hessenberg form** or to be a **lower Hessenberg matrix** if its transpose {\displaystyle } ({\displaystyle }) is an upper Hessenberg matrix or equivalently if $a_{i,j}=0$ for all $i,j$ with $j>i+1$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A lower Hessenberg matrix is called **unreduced** if all superdiagonal entries are nonzero, i.e. if $a_{i,i+1}\neq 0$ for all $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n-1\}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The matrix A is an upper unreduced Hessenberg matrix, B is a lower unreduced Hessenberg matrix and C is a lower Hessenberg matrix but is not unreduced.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Many linear algebra algorithms require significantly less computational effort when applied to triangular matrices, and this improvement often carries over to Hessenberg matrices as well.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] If the constraints of a linear algebra problem do not allow a general matrix to be conveniently reduced to a triangular one, reduction to Hessenberg form is often the next best thing.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] In fact, reduction of any matrix to a Hessenberg form can be achieved in a finite number of steps (for example, through Householder's transformation of unitary similarity transforms).
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Subsequent reduction of Hessenberg matrix to a triangular matrix can be achieved through iterative procedures, such as shifted QR-factorization.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] In eigenvalue algorithms, the Hessenberg matrix can be further reduced to a triangular matrix through Shifted QR-factorization combined with deflation steps.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Reducing a general matrix to a Hessenberg matrix and then reducing further to a triangular matrix, instead of directly reducing a general matrix to a triangular matrix, often economizes the arithmetic involved in the QR algorithm for eigenvalue problems.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Any $n\times n$ matrix can be transformed into a Hessenberg matrix by a similarity transformation using Householder transformations.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The following procedure for such a transformation is adapted from **A Second Course In Linear Algebra** by *Garcia & Horn*.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Let A be any real or complex $n\times n$ matrix, then let $A^{\prime }$ be the $(n-1)\times n$ submatrix of A constructed by removing the first row in A and let $\mathbf {a} _{1}^{\prime }$ be the first column of $A'$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Now construct $V_{3}$ and then $U_{3}$ in a similar manner, but for the matrix $A^{\prime \prime \prime }$ constructed by removing the first row and first column of $A^{\prime \prime }$ and proceed as in the previous steps.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] Continue like this for a total of $n-2$ steps.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] By construction of $U_{k}$ , the first k columns of any $n\times n$ matrix are invariant under multiplication by $U_{k}^{*}$ from the right.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] reduces the matrix A to the lower Hessenberg form.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] For $n\in \{1,2\}$ , every $n\times n$ matrix is both upper Hessenberg, and lower Hessenberg.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The product of a Hessenberg matrix with a triangular matrix is again Hessenberg.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] More precisely, if A is upper Hessenberg and T is upper triangular, then $AT$ and $TA$ are upper Hessenberg.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The Hessenberg matrix can be presented in a Jordan canonical form, with confluent Vandermonde matrix as the similarity matrix (chapter 1.4.2 of ).
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A matrix that is both upper Hessenberg and lower Hessenberg is a tridiagonal matrix, of which the Jacobi matrix is an important example.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] This includes the symmetric or Hermitian Hessenberg matrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] A Hermitian matrix can be reduced to tri-diagonal real symmetric matrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The Hessenberg operator is an infinite dimensional Hessenberg matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] It commonly occurs as the generalization of the Jacobi operator to a system of orthogonal polynomials for the space of square-integrable holomorphic functions over some domain—that is, a Bergman space.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] The eigenvalues of each principal submatrix of the Hessenberg operator are given by the characteristic polynomial for that submatrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/hessenberg-matrix] These polynomials are called the Bergman polynomials, and provide an orthogonal polynomial basis for Bergman space.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] In linear algebra, a **QR decomposition**, also known as a **QR factorization** or **QU factorization**, is a decomposition of a matrix *A* into a product *A* = *QR* of an orthonormal matrix *Q* and an upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is often used to solve the linear least squares (LLS) problem and is the basis for a particular eigenvalue algorithm, the QR algorithm.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] where *Q* is an orthogonal matrix (its columns are orthogonal unit vectors meaning $Q^{\textsf {T}}=Q^{-1}$ ) and *R* is an upper triangular matrix (also called right triangular matrix).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] If *A* is invertible, then the factorization is unique if we require the diagonal elements of *R* to be positive.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] If instead *A* is a complex square matrix, then there is a decomposition *A* = *QR* where *Q* is a unitary matrix (so the conjugate transpose $Q^{\dagger }=Q^{-1}$ ).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] If *A* has *n* linearly independent columns, then the first *n* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the column space of *A*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] More generally, the first *k* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the span of the first *k* columns of *A* for any 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The fact that any column *k* of *A* only depends on the first *k* columns of *Q* corresponds to the triangular form of *R*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] More generally, we can factor a complex *m*×*n* matrix *A*, with *m* ≥ *n*, as the product of an *m*×*m* unitary matrix *Q* and an *m*×*n* upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Golub & Van Loan (1996, §5.2) call *Q*1*R*1 the *thin QR factorization* of *A*; Trefethen and Bau call this the *reduced QR factorization*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] If *A* is of full rank *n* and we require that the diagonal elements of *R*1 are positive then *R*1 and *Q*1 are unique, but in general *Q*2 is not.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] *R*1 is then equal to the upper triangular factor of the Cholesky decomposition of *A** *A* (= *A*T*A* if *A* is real).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Analogously, we can define QL, RQ, and LQ decompositions, with *L* being a *lower* triangular matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] There are several methods for actually computing the QR decomposition, such as the Gram–Schmidt process, Householder transformations, or Givens rotations.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Each has a number of advantages and disadvantages.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Recall that an orthonormal matrix Q has the property $Q^{\textsf {T}}Q=I$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The RQ decomposition transforms a matrix *A* into the product of an upper triangular matrix *R* (also known as right-triangular) and an orthogonal matrix *Q*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The only difference from QR decomposition is the order of these matrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of columns of *A*, started from the first column.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] RQ decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of rows of *A*, started from the last row.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The Gram-Schmidt process is inherently numerically unstable.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] While the application of the projections has an appealing geometric analogy to orthogonalization, the orthogonalization itself is prone to numerical error.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] A significant advantage is the ease of implementation.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] A Householder reflection (or *Householder transformation*) is a transformation that takes a vector and reflects it about some plane or hyperplane.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We can use this operation to calculate the *QR* factorization of an *m*-by-*n* matrix A with *m* ≥ *n*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary real *m*-dimensional column vector of A such that $\|\mathbf {x} \|=|\alpha |$ for a scalar *α*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] *α* should get the same sign as the k -th coordinate of $\mathbf {x}$ , where $x_{k}$ is to be the pivot coordinate after which all entries are 0 in matrix *A*'s final upper triangular form.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] and substitute transposition by conjugate transposition in the construction of *Q* below.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This can be used to gradually transform an *m*-by-*n* matrix *A* to upper triangular form.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] First, we multiply *A* with the Householder matrix *Q*1 we obtain when we choose the first matrix column for **x**.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This results in a matrix *Q*1*A* with zeros in the left column (except for the first row).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This can be repeated for *A*′ (obtained from *Q*1*A* by deleting the first row and first column), resulting in a Householder matrix *Q*′2.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This method has greater numerical stability than the Gram–Schmidt method above.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The following table gives the number of operations in the *k*-th step of the QR-decomposition by the Householder transformation, assuming a square matrix with size *n*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] so we already have almost a triangular matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] after performing a direct sum with 1 to make sure the next step in the process works properly.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The matrix *Q* is orthogonal and *R* is upper triangular, so *A* = *QR* is the required QR decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The use of Householder transformations is inherently the most simple of the numerically stable QR decomposition algorithms due to the use of reflections as the mechanism for producing zeroes in the *R* matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] However, the Householder reflection algorithm is bandwidth heavy and difficult to parallelize, as every reflection that produces a new zero element changes the entirety of both *Q* and *R* matrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The Householder QR method can be implemented in parallel with algorithms such as the TSQR algorithm (which stands for *Tall Skinny QR*).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This algorithm can be applied in the case when the matrix *A* has *m >> n*.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This algorithm uses a binary reduction tree to compute local householder QR decomposition at each node in the forward pass, and re-constitute the Q matrix in the backward pass.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The binary tree structure aims at decreasing the amount of communication between processor to increase performance.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] QR decompositions can also be computed with a series of Givens rotations.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Each rotation zeroes an element in the subdiagonal of the matrix, forming the *R* matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The concatenation of all the Givens rotations forms the orthogonal *Q* matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] In practice, Givens rotations are not actually performed by building a whole matrix and doing a matrix multiplication.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] A Givens rotation procedure is used instead which does the equivalent of the sparse Givens matrix multiplication, without the extra work of handling the sparse elements.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The Givens rotation procedure is useful in situations where only relatively few off-diagonal elements need to be zeroed, and is more easily parallelized than Householder transformations.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] First, we need to form a rotation matrix that will zero the lowermost left element, $a_{31}=-4$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We form this matrix using the Givens rotation method, and call the matrix $G_{1}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We will first rotate the vector ${\begin{bmatrix}12&-4\end{bmatrix}}$ , to point along the *X* axis.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] And the result of $G_{1}A$ now has a zero in the $a_{31}$ element.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We can similarly form Givens matrices $G_{2}$ and $G_{3}$ , which will zero the sub-diagonal elements $a_{21}$ and $a_{32}$ , forming a triangular matrix R .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The orthogonal matrix $Q^{\textsf {T}}$ is formed from the product of all the Givens matrices $Q^{\textsf {T}}=G_{3}G_{2}G_{1}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The QR decomposition via Givens rotations is the most involved to implement, as the ordering of the rows required to fully exploit the algorithm is not trivial to determine.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] However, it has a significant advantage in that each new zero element $a_{ij}$ affects only the row with the element to be zeroed (*i*) and a row above (*j*).
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This makes the Givens rotation algorithm more bandwidth efficient and parallelizable than the Householder reflection technique.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] It is possible to compute the QR decomposition in a fast way with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We can use QR decomposition to find the determinant of a square matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Suppose a matrix is decomposed as $A=QR$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] where the $r_{ii}$ are the entries on the diagonal of R .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] where the $\lambda _{i}$ are eigenvalues of A .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] We can extend the above properties to a non-square complex matrix A by introducing the definition of QR decomposition for non-square complex matrices and replacing eigenvalues with singular values.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] where 0 denotes the zero matrix and Q is a unitary matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] where the $\sigma _{i}$ are the singular values of A .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Note that the singular values of A and R are identical, although their complex eigenvalues may be different.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] It follows that the QR decomposition can be used to efficiently calculate the product of the eigenvalues or singular values of a matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Column pivoting is useful when *A* is (nearly) rank deficient, or is suspected of being so.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] *P* is usually chosen so that the diagonal elements of *R* are non-increasing: $\left|r_{11}\right|\geq \left|r_{22}\right|\geq \cdots \geq \left|r_{nn}\right|$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] This can be used to find the (numerical) rank of *A* at lower computational cost than a singular value decomposition, forming the basis of so-called rank-revealing QR algorithms.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Compared to the direct matrix inverse, inverse solutions using QR decomposition are more numerically stable as evidenced by their reduced condition numbers.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Here $R_{1}$ is a square $m\times m$ right triangular matrix, and the zero matrix has dimension $(n-m)\times m$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The latter technique enjoys greater numerical accuracy and lower computations.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] To find a solution ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ to the overdetermined ( $m\geq n$ ) problem $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ which minimizes the norm $\left\|A{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {b} \right\|$ , first find the QR factorization of A : $A=QR$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] The solution can then be expressed as ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}=R_{1}^{-1}\left(Q_{1}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {b} \right)$ , where $Q_{1}$ is an $m\times n$ matrix containing the first n columns of the full orthonormal basis Q and where $R_{1}$ is as before.
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Equivalent to the underdetermined case, back substitution can be used to quickly and accurately find this ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ without explicitly inverting $R_{1}$ .
[src:qr-algorithm/qr-decomposition] Iwasawa decomposition generalizes QR decomposition to semi-simple Lie groups.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] In linear algebra, the **Schur decomposition** or **Schur triangulation**, named after Issai Schur, is a matrix decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] It allows one to write an arbitrary complex square matrix as unitarily similar to an upper triangular matrix whose diagonal elements are the eigenvalues of the original matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] The complex Schur decomposition reads as follows: if A is an *n* × *n* square matrix with complex entries, then *A* can be expressed as $A=QUQ^{-1}$ for some unitary matrix *Q* (so that the inverse *Q*−1 is also the conjugate transpose *Q** of *Q*), and some upper triangular matrix *U*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Since *U* is similar to *A*, it has the same spectrum, and since it is triangular, its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries of *U*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Phrased somewhat differently, the first part says that a linear operator *J* on a complex finite-dimensional vector space stabilizes a complete flag (*V*1, ..., *Vn*).
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] There is also a real Schur decomposition.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] If A is an *n* × *n* square matrix with real entries, then *A* can be expressed as $A=QHQ^{-1}$ where Q is an orthogonal matrix and H is either upper or lower quasi-triangular.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] A quasi-triangular matrix is a matrix that when expressed as a block matrix of *2* × *2* and *1* × *1* blocks is triangular.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] This is a stronger property than being Hessenberg.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Just as in the complex case, a family of commuting real matrices {*Ai*} may be simultaneously brought to quasi-triangular form by an orthogonal matrix.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] There exists an orthogonal matrix *Q* such that, for every *Ai* in the given family, $H_{i}=QA_{i}Q^{-1}$ is upper quasi-triangular.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] A constructive proof for the Schur decomposition is as follows: every operator *A* on a complex finite-dimensional vector space has an eigenvalue *λ*, corresponding to some eigenspace *Vλ*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] The above matrix would be upper-triangular except for the *A*22 block.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] But exactly the same procedure can be applied to the sub-matrix *A*22, viewed as an operator on *Vλ*⊥, and its submatrices.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Continue this way until the resulting matrix is upper triangular.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Since each conjugation increases the dimension of the upper-triangular block by at least one, this process takes at most *n* steps.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Thus the space **C***n* will be exhausted and the procedure has yielded the desired result.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] The above argument can be slightly restated as follows: let *λ* be an eigenvalue of *A*, corresponding to some eigenspace *Vλ*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] *A* induces an operator *T* on the quotient space **C***n*/*Vλ*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] This operator is precisely the *A*22 submatrix from above.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] As before, *T* would have an eigenspace, say *Wμ* ⊂ **C***n* modulo *Vλ*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Notice the preimage of *Wμ* under the quotient map is an invariant subspace of *A* that contains *Vλ*.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Continue this way until the resulting quotient space has dimension 0.
[src:qr-algorithm/schur-decomposition] Then the successive preimages of the eigenspaces found at each step form a flag that *A* stabilizes.
